  "prompt": "Is there a consensus that money laundering is against the law?",
  "response": "Yes, there is a global consensus that money laundering is against the law.\n\nHere's why:\n\n*   **International Treaties and Conventions:** The United Nations, the Financial Action Task Force (FATF), and other international bodies have established frameworks and standards that criminalize money laundering and encourage international cooperation to combat it.\n*   **National Laws:** Virtually every country in the world has enacted laws that make money laundering a criminal offense. These laws typically prohibit concealing or disguising the proceeds of illegal activities to make them appear legitimate.\n*   **Public Policy:** Money laundering facilitates a wide range of serious crimes, including drug trafficking, terrorism, corruption, and human trafficking. Criminalizing it is a key element of efforts to combat these underlying crimes and protect the integrity of the financial system.\n*   **Widespread condemnation:** The fact that money laundering facilitates crime has led to widespread condemnation by civil society, law enforcement, and governments around the world.\n\nTherefore, there is a strong and universal consensus that money laundering is against the law.",
